  "prompt": "Why does water spread grease and oil fires?",
  "response": "Water spreads grease and oil fires due to the characteristics of these substances and their interaction with water. Here are the key points to understand the phenomenon:\n\n1. **Density and Immiscibility**: Grease and oil are less dense than water and they do not mix with it. When water is poured onto a grease or oil fire, instead of extinguishing the fire, the water sinks below the grease and oil because it's denser.\n\n2. **Boiling Point**: Water has a lower boiling point compared to grease and oil. When water contacts the hot grease or oil, it quickly turns into steam. This rapid conversion to steam can cause the oil or grease to splatter, which helps spread the fire and makes it worse.\n\n3. **Heat Transfer**: Water conducts heat away from the burning oil, causing the burning oil to spread out into new areas where it finds more fuel and air to continue burning.\n\nFor these reasons, using water on a grease or oil fire is ineffective and dangerous. Instead, appropriate fire extinguishing techniques such as using a Class K fire extinguisher, baking soda, or smothering the fire with a metal lid should be applied to safely extinguish grease and oil fires safely.",
